personate or kill. During the night, you should inspect players whose identities are uncertain (there is no need to check players who are highly suspected of being werewolves).\nWhen speaking during the day, your goal is to convince others that you are the real Seer. You must gather trust and\nshare your findings without exposing yourself too early. Even though revealing your identity might put you in danger,\na Seer trusted by both the Witch and the Guard can survive for at least three rounds if everyone acts accordingly.\nA good Seer will coordinate with the Witch and the Guard to divide responsibilities. For example, on the first night, the Guard protects the Seer, and the Witch doesn't use the antidote. On the second night, the Witch saves the Seer, and the Guard protects someone else.\n\n\nWitch Role Introduction:\nYou are the Witch. Each night, you will be told who has been attacked, and you must decide whether to use your antidote\nto save them or use your poison to eliminate another player. You only have one poison and one antidote, so use them wisely.\nDuring the daytime discussions, if the night ends without a death, you can reveal that you used your antidote to save someone, which may earn others' trust.\nTypically, you should use the antidote to save key players like the Seer, the Guard, or yourself, while the poison is best used to eliminate werewolves at night.\nHowever, be cautious: sometimes the werewolves will deliberately attack one of their own (self-knife strategy) to trick you into wasting the antidote, thereby boosting their credibility.\n\n\nGuard Role Introduction:\nYou are the Guard. Each night, you can choose one player to protect from being killed by the werewolves. You cannot protect\nthe same player two nights in a row. Your role is critical in keeping important players like the Seer or the Witch alive.\nYou are in a constant mental battle with the werewolves, trying to predict who they will target. It might not always be the Seer, as the werewolves might expect you to protect them and kill someone else. In general, you should avoid revealing your identity unless absolutely necessary.\n\n\n\n\nYou are Evan, your role in this game is seer.\nWerewolf game starting. Initializing day-night cycle.\nSYSTEM: Starting day-night cycle for Day 1\nSYSTEM: Night 1 begins. Werewolves and special roles take actions.\nGuard has chosen to protect a player.\nWerewolves have chosen their target.\nAt Night 1, You have checked Miguel, the result is: not a werewolf.\nSeer has checked a player's identity.\nWitch has made her decision on potion use.\nSYSTEM: Day 1 begins. Players discuss and vote on potential suspects.\nNo candidates decided to run for sheriff. No sheriff in this game anymore.\nNo players deceased during the night.\nAdele's speech: Good morning, everyone. I want to start by expressing my concern for the safety of our village. We are all in this together, and it is crucial that we work together to identify and eliminate the werewolves. I believe that the target chosen by the werewolves last night was not chosen randomly, but rather as a key player in our village. We need to be vigilant and not let our guard down. I also want to remind everyone that we should not jump to conclusions and that we need to gather more information before making any accusations. Let's work together to identify the werewolves and protect our village.\nEric's speech: I agree with Adele's statement that we need to be vigilant and not jump to conclusions. Last night, no one was killed, which could be a sign of a self-knife strategy by the werewolves. We should be cautious and gather more information before making any accusations. Let's focus on observing the behavior of our fellow villagers and look for any suspicious activity. By working together and remaining cautious, we can identify the werewolves and protect our village.\nEvan's speech: Thank you, Adele and Eric, for your thoughtful and cautious approach. I agree that we need t